			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="448">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>&ldquo;<a href="/article/4695">Of All the Mothers in the World</a>,&rdquo; by Heather King [August 2012], was a wonderful essay. One sentence really stuck with me: &ldquo;If you&rsquo;re single, you carry the added weight, the secret shame, of knowing that you are first in no one&rsquo;s heart.&rdquo; As a single woman of fifty-one (divorced for eleven years), I know what she means. I don&rsquo;t normally go around feeling sorry for myself, but I&rsquo;ve never read such a poignant description of being alone.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Jennie Renfrow Ibarguen<br>St. Petersburg, Florida</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="449">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>I enjoyed reading Heather King&rsquo;s &ldquo;Of All the Mothers in the World,&rdquo; but I must disagree when she says that if you&rsquo;re single, &ldquo;you are first in no one&rsquo;s heart.&rdquo;</p>

<p>It&rsquo;s no different for those who are in a relationship. We are almost never first in anyone&rsquo;s heart. There are children, careers, elderly parents, chronic illnesses, and sometimes just plain selfish considerations that take the top spots. Most married people are doing well if they manage to be third or fourth in their spouse&rsquo;s heart. I know that in twenty-five years I&rsquo;ve never managed to place higher than third. Almost anyone who has been married for a few decades will say the same, if they&rsquo;re honest.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Name Withheld<br></p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="442">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Thank you for printing Heather King&rsquo;s essay &ldquo;<a href="/article/4695">Of All the Mothers in the World</a>&rdquo; [August 2012]. I read it on my front porch on a glorious fall morning and wept: For the author&rsquo;s fear that screaming for help would bring no one. For her deep love of her flawed mother. For the difficulty she had justifying a small indulgence.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Dana Brinson<br>Chapel Hill, North Carolina</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

